1. What is the main purpose of gridlines in Google Sheets?


Gridlines are the faint horizontal/vertical lines separating cells, creating a visual grid structure. Their main purpose is data organization and cell boundary definition for easier navigation and entry.​

Core Functions:



   Define cell boundaries



   Guide eye alignment across rows/columns



   Help during data entry/formatting



   Maintain visual structure


2. How do gridlines help in data readability?

Gridlines prevent "wall of text" effect by breaking data into neat cells:


| Without Gridlines   | With Gridlines             |

| ------------------- | -------------------------- |

| Data runs together  | Clear cell separation      |

| Hard to follow rows | Easy horizontal tracking   |

| Columns blur        | Vertical alignment obvious |

| Eye strain          | Structured appearance      |



Especially helpful for:

   Large datasets

   Number-heavy sheets

   Team collaboration

   Dense tables



3. What is the difference between gridlines and borders?



| Aspect        | Gridlines              | Borders                   |

| ------------- | ---------------------- | ------------------------- |

| Default       | Always on (faint gray) | Must be added manually    |

| Print         | Optional setting       | Always prints             |

| Customization | Show/hide only         | Color, thickness, style   |

| Purpose       | Screen navigation      | Printed reports, emphasis |

| Location      | View → Show gridlines  | Format → Borders          |



Toggle Gridlines: View → Show → Gridlines ✅​


4. How do you print gridlines?



Enable for printing:



1.    File → Print (or Ctrl+P)
   
2.    Formatting section → Show gridlines checkbox
   
3.    Preview shows gridlines
   
4.    Print → Lines appear on paper



Pro Tip: Use borders instead for reliable printing (gridlines sometimes fail).







5. When should gridlines be hidden for better design?



Hide for cleaner design when:



| Scenario            | Why Hide                         |

| ------------------- | -------------------------------- |

| Final reports       | Custom borders look professional |

| Charts-heavy sheets | Less visual clutter              |

| Dashboard design    | Focus on data highlights         |

| Printed documents   | Borders give better control      |

| Colorful formatting | Gridlines fight with colors      |



Hide: View → Show → Gridlines ❌



Best Practice:



text

Data entry → Gridlines ON

Final presentation → Gridlines OFF + Custom borders



Gridlines = working tool, borders = presentation polish! ✨

